<p>For Minneapolis's cold climate, high-efficiency furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher are essential, paired with air conditioning units rated at least 16 SEER for optimal performance. However, modern cold-climate heat pumps are becoming increasingly popular, as newer models can operate efficiently down to -13¬∞F and provide both heating and cooling. Given that Minneapolis homes typically need heating 6-7 months per year versus only 2-3 months of significant cooling, prioritizing heating efficiency is crucial. Gas furnaces remain the most cost-effective heating option for most homes, but electric heat pumps offer superior efficiency and qualify for substantial rebates. For optimal year-round comfort, consider a dual-fuel system combining a heat pump with a backup gas furnace for the coldest days.</p>

